<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-178-146  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 178 146.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  March 20 1989 n530 pS17(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Producing software en masse.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Banin, Ram.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The use of integrated project support environments (IPSEs) as aframework for software development can enable the rapid productionof high-quality code, as is exemplified by the use of IPSE-likeframeworks in the software factories of large Japanesecorporations.andP;  IPSEs are needed because of the software crisis inthe US, Japan, and Europe that has resulted from the rapidincrease in the size, complexity, and number of needed softwareapplications.andP;  This crisis must be addressed at the technologylevel through the increased use of automation in softwaredevelopment and at the management level through the use of IPSEsto handle the administrative tasks.andP;  An IPSE offers projectmanagement, system administration, networking, and programminginterface tools.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Project ManagementSoftware PackagesProduct DevelopmentProgram Development TechniquesApplicationsProductivityProgramming ManagementAutomation.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Geometric mean length of code by company size. (table)Development of very large programs by company size. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>